REQUIREMENTS:
- labels: exactly one entry per destination above, {"to": N, "label": "..."}.
- A label is a SHORT ACTION in the player's voice: an imperative verb and its
  object — the move the player makes. "Enter the diner", "Descend to the mill
  basement", "Open the journal", "Order the arrests". Aim for a handful of
  words: a label is a button the player clicks, not a sentence.
- The mood and scenery are already carried by the prose the reader just read
  and by the scene they are about to enter — so keep them OUT of the label. The
  tone lives in the VERB you choose ("slip into" vs "stride into"), never in an
  atmospheric clause tacked on: "Enter the diner" is right; "Enter the diner,
  the firepit ablaze with the ledger" is the failure this rule exists to
  prevent. Do not append a "…, the X <-ing>" clause or bolt a named object on
  for flavour.
- No meta-language — "continue", "go to the next scene" are failures; a single
  onward choice still names a concrete act in the character's own diction.
{% if dests | length > 1 %}- Labels leaving this passage must differ by naming different ACTIONS, not by
  piling different scenery onto the same move.
{% endif %}- Never mention flags, dilemmas, or structure in a label.
{% if is_rendering %}
- THIS PASSAGE is one rendering of a cosmetic fork, rejoining a road the reader
  could have walked plainly. Its rejoin label should read differently from
  simply walking on — but that difference lives in the ACTION and diction (a
  wearier verb, a different thing the character reaches for), still a short
  clean action, NOT a mood clause tacked onto it. Never re-offer an action a
  parallel passage already labels onto the same destination (marked ALREADY
  OFFERED above): same road reached, a different move made.
{% endif %}
